# Diary of Alex Chen: The Frustrated Millennial Professional

## Entry 1: Before Using the Product (The Breaking Point)

*11:42 PM, Tuesday*

I’m so tired I can feel it behind my eyes—a dull, throbbing ache that never really goes away. I just spent the last two hours staring at my Vanguard dashboard, and honestly, I want to throw my laptop out the window. 

I make $145,000 a year. I’m supposed to be "successful." I did everything they told me to do. I got the CS degree, I landed the senior engineering role, I max out my 401(k), I dollar-cost average into VTSAX every single month like a good little robot. And for what? So I can watch my portfolio inch upward at a glacial 7% a year while a one-bedroom condo in this city jumps another $50k in six months? It’s a sick joke. 

I was looking at Zillow earlier, and the anxiety just gripped my chest like a vice. I’m never going to catch up. The math literally doesn’t work. Inflation is a silent thief, and it’s stealing my future right out from under me. 

I see these guys on Reddit and YouTube—some 22-year-old kid making $30k a month day trading options or riding some crypto wave. And part of me hates them, but a bigger part of me is just… jealous. They found an edge. I’m just grinding away in the corporate machine, chained to my desk, writing code for a company that would replace me in a heartbeat. 

I tried day trading last year. I put $5k into Robinhood, thought my analytical brain could beat the market. I lost half of it in three weeks. The emotional rollercoaster was nauseating. I can’t do that again. I don’t have the mental bandwidth to stare at candlestick charts while I’m supposed to be in a sprint planning meeting. 

There has to be a better way. I know the hedge funds use algorithms. I know the game is rigged in favor of institutional money. I just need a tool—a system, a piece of software—that can do the heavy lifting for me. Because if I have to wait until I’m 65 to actually live my life, I’m going to lose my mind. I feel like I’m suffocating in a velvet lined trap.

